BACKGROUND	O
OF	O
THE	O
INVENTION	O
This	O
invention	O
relates	O
to	O
a	O
system	O
for	O
pattern	O
recognition	O
that	O
is	O
particularly	O
useful	O
for	O
recognizing	O
speech	O
and	O
handwriting	O
.	O

Speech	O
recognition	O
may	O
be	O
defined	O
as	O
the	O
extraction	O
of	O
a	O
sequence	O
of	O
symbols	O
from	O
a	O
continuous	O
stream	O
of	O
auditory	O
data	O
.	O
In	O
handwriting	O
recognition	O
,	O
such	O
sequence	O
of	O
symbols	O
is	O
extracted	O
from	O
visual	O
data	O
.	O
By	O
using	O
this	O
invention	O
,	O
a	O
machine	O
recognizes	O
speech	O
or	O
handwriting	O
as	O
competently	O
as	O
humans	O
.	O

Personal	O
experience	O
as	O
well	O
as	O
linguistic	O
theory	O
give	O
us	O
the	O
strong	O
impression	O
that	O
certain	O
identifiable	O
sounds	O
,	O
which	O
we	O
call	O
phonemes	O
,	O
form	O
the	O
basis	O
of	O
the	O
symbolic	O
structure	O
that	O
is	O
language	O
.	O
The	O
use	O
of	O
phonetic	O
transcription	O
of	O
speech	O
is	O
not	O
restricted	O
to	O
academic	O
purposes	O
.	O
It	O
is	O
pervasively	O
practised	O
in	O
stenograph	O
reporting	O
in	O
courts	O
of	O
law	O
and	O
congressional	O
hearings	O
.	O

However	O
,	O
machine	O
recognition	O
of	O
phonemes	O
is	O
notoriously	O
difficult	O
.	O
Contextual	O
effects	O
,	O
known	O
as	O
coarticulation	O
,	O
variability	O
within	O
one	O
speaker	O
,	O
as	O
well	O
as	O
from	O
speaker	O
to	O
speaker	O
,	O
lead	O
to	O
multiple	O
manifestations	O
of	O
the	O
same	O
underlying	O
phoneme	O
.	O
Nevertheless	O
,	O
humans	O
or	O
,	O
for	O
that	O
matter	O
,	O
animals	O
such	O
as	O
dogs	O
and	O
cats	O
,	O
have	O
little	O
difficulty	O
in	O
recognizing	O
spoken	O
sounds	O
.	O
Furthermore	O
,	O
humans	O
are	O
able	O
to	O
do	O
so	O
against	O
a	O
background	O
of	O
noise	O
or	O
distraction	O
,	O
commonly	O
referred	O
to	O
as	O
the	O
cocktail	O
party	O
syndrome	O
.	O

In	O
the	O
past	O
few	O
years	O
,	O
one	O
approach	O
,	O
referred	O
to	O
as	O
HMM	O
(	O
Hidden	O
Markov	O
Models	O
)	O
,	O
has	O
been	O
successful	O
in	O
dealing	O
with	O
the	O
variability	O
in	O
speech	O
.	O
This	O
approach	O
has	O
achieved	O
high	O
performance	O
in	O
terms	O
of	O
accuracy	O
,	O
but	O
requires	O
extensive	O
modeling	O
of	O
the	O
particular	O
language	O
being	O
used	O
.	O
In	O
essence	O
,	O
the	O
approach	O
compensates	O
for	O
an	O
inadequate	O
representation	O
of	O
individual	O
speech	O
events	O
by	O
astutely	O
guessing	O
the	O
best	O
match	O
over	O
a	O
sequence	O
of	O
such	O
events	O
.	O
It	O
captures	O
the	O
statistical	O
properties	O
of	O
sequences	O
of	O
events	O
in	O
the	O
parameters	O
of	O
the	O
models	O
.	O
It	O
achieves	O
this	O
high	O
performance	O
through	O
a	O
thorough	O
statistical	O
accounting	O
of	O
the	O
particular	O
body	O
of	O
speech	O
data	O
used	O
to	O
train	O
the	O
models	O
and	O
an	O
efficient	O
method	O
of	O
searching	O
through	O
a	O
large	O
number	O
of	O
hypotheses	O
for	O
the	O
best	O
match	O
.	O
Because	O
of	O
this	O
,	O
the	O
performance	O
degrades	O
rapidly	O
in	O
the	O
face	O
of	O
noise	O
,	O
novel	O
speech	O
or	O
non-speech	O
sounds	O
,	O
that	O
is	O
,	O
in	O
real-life	O
environments	O
.	O
The	O
problem	O
of	O
novel	O
speech	O
may	O
be	O
solved	O
by	O
a	O
more	O
comprehensive	O
set	O
of	O
models	O
,	O
but	O
this	O
entails	O
ever	O
greater	O
demand	O
for	O
searching	O
.	O

In	O
contrast	O
,	O
neural	O
networks	O
,	O
the	O
only	O
other	O
significant	O
approach	O
,	O
is	O
tolerant	O
of	O
noise	O
,	O
generalizes	O
well	O
,	O
and	O
requires	O
relatively	O
modest	O
amount	O
of	O
computational	O
power	O
in	O
actual	O
performance	O
.	O
This	O
approach	O
has	O
achieved	O
results	O
superior	O
to	O
that	O
of	O
HMM	O
in	O
the	O
recognition	O
of	O
isolated	O
phonemes	O
from	O
one	O
speaker	O
,	O
but	O
has	O
difficulty	O
with	O
fluent	O
speech	O
and	O
true	O
speaker	O
independence	O
.	O

It	O
is	O
therefore	O
desirable	O
to	O
provide	O
a	O
pattern	O
recognition	O
system	O
in	O
which	O
these	O
difficulties	O
in	O
both	O
approaches	O
described	O
above	O
are	O
overcome	O
.	O

SUMMARY	O
OF	O
THE	O
INVENTION	O
One	O
objective	O
of	O
this	O
invention	O
is	O
to	O
improve	O
the	O
machine	O
recognition	O
of	O
phonemes	O
from	O
fluent	O
speech	O
,	O
spoken	O
by	O
familiar	O
or	O
new	O
speakers	O
,	O
in	O
any	O
language	O
,	O
in	O
everyday	O
noisy	O
circumstances	O
,	O
to	O
the	O
level	O
of	O
performance	O
of	O
humans	O
.	O

As	O
will	O
be	O
evident	O
from	O
this	O
disclosure	O
,	O
only	O
the	O
first	O
stage	O
of	O
this	O
invention	O
deals	O
with	O
auditory	O
signal	O
processing	O
.	O
The	O
later	O
stages	O
deal	O
with	O
any	O
two-dimensional	O
signals	O
.	O
Insofar	O
as	O
the	O
difficulties	O
of	O
recognizing	O
written	O
symbols	O
from	O
continuous	O
handwriting	O
are	O
similar	O
to	O
those	O
of	O
recognizing	O
phonemes	O
from	O
continuous	O
speech	O
,	O
it	O
is	O
a	O
second	O
objective	O
of	O
this	O
invention	O
to	O
recognize	O
continuous	O
handwriting	O
.	O

In	O
conventional	O
speech	O
recognition	O
systems	O
,	O
the	O
acoustic	O
signal	O
is	O
regarded	O
as	O
a	O
one-dimensional	O
signal	O
.	O
Frequency	O
content	O
of	O
the	O
signal	O
,	O
obtained	O
usually	O
by	O
Fourier	O
transform	O
techniques	O
,	O
is	O
therefore	O
regarded	O
as	O
capturing	O
all	O
of	O
the	O
relevant	O
information	O
.	O
This	O
invention	O
is	O
based	O
on	O
the	O
inventor	O
's	O
insight	O
that	O
speech	O
,	O
or	O
more	O
generally	O
,	O
sound	O
,	O
as	O
processed	O
by	O
human	O
beings	O
,	O
or	O
even	O
animals	O
,	O
must	O
be	O
as	O
literally	O
represented	O
by	O
two-dimensional	O
pictures	O
as	O
vision	O
.	O
This	O
invention	O
asserts	O
that	O
speech	O
recognition	O
,	O
in	O
any	O
language	O
,	O
is	O
founded	O
on	O
the	O
texture	O
of	O
sound	O
.	O
In	O
other	O
words	O
,	O
the	O
applicant	O
recognized	O
that	O
,	O
in	O
addition	O
to	O
frequency	O
of	O
the	O
tones	O
present	O
in	O
speech	O
,	O
timing	O
information	O
concerning	O
when	O
significant	O
tonotopic	O
events	O
happen	O
is	O
also	O
critical	O
for	O
recognizing	O
speech	O
.	O
Therefore	O
,	O
in	O
addition	O
to	O
the	O
detection	O
of	O
the	O
presence	O
of	O
significant	O
tones	O
in	O
speech	O
,	O
change	O
in	O
significant	O
tones	O
over	O
time	O
is	O
also	O
important	O
.	O

This	O
invention	O
proposes	O
a	O
multitude	O
of	O
filters	O
with	O
two-dimensional	O
outputs	O
ordered	O
in	O
frequency	O
and	O
time	O
for	O
extracting	O
the	O
texture	O
of	O
sound	O
,	O
and	O
for	O
the	O
formation	O
of	O
the	O
compact	O
units	O
of	O
sound	O
,	O
i	O
.	O
e	O
.	O
,	O
phonemes	O
,	O
from	O
the	O
texture	O
.	O

The	O
ordering	O
of	O
filter	O
outputs	O
in	O
frequency	O
is	O
referred	O
to	O
below	O
as	O
"	O
tonotopy	O
.	O
"	O
The	O
texture	O
of	O
sound	O
is	O
embodied	O
in	O
elementary	O
tonotopic	O
features	O
.	O
These	O
are	O
filter	O
outputs	O
indicating	O
the	O
presence	O
of	O
any	O
significant	O
tones	O
,	O
and	O
the	O
change	O
in	O
significant	O
tones	O
over	O
time	O
.	O
In	O
the	O
preferred	O
embodiment	O
,	O
the	O
elementary	O
tonotopic	O
features	O
may	O
include	O
onset	O
,	O
rise	O
and	O
fall	O
of	O
any	O
significant	O
tones	O
of	O
the	O
sound	O
signal	O
.	O
The	O
term	O
"	O
onset	O
"	O
refers	O
to	O
the	O
timing	O
of	O
initiation	O
or	O
cessation	O
of	O
significant	O
tones	O
.	O
As	O
a	O
further	O
improvement	O
,	O
the	O
elementary	O
tonotopic	O
features	O
may	O
also	O
include	O
the	O
frequencies	O
of	O
any	O
significant	O
tones	O
.	O

One	O
aspect	O
of	O
the	O
invention	O
is	O
directed	O
towards	O
a	O
system	O
and	O
method	O
for	O
recognizing	O
patterns	O
in	O
an	O
input	O
signal	O
where	O
the	O
input	O
signal	O
contains	O
tonotopic	O
information	O
.	O
The	O
method	O
for	O
recognizing	O
patterns	O
in	O
an	O
input	O
signal	O
containing	O
tonotopic	O
information	O
comprises	O
first	O
filtering	O
the	O
input	O
speech	O
signal	O
to	O
provide	O
a	O
filtered	O
output	O
,	O
said	O
output	O
indicating	O
the	O
tonotopic	O
characteristics	O
of	O
said	O
input	O
signal	O
over	O
a	O
time	O
period	O
.	O
The	O
method	O
further	O
comprises	O
filtering	O
said	O
output	O
to	O
provide	O
an	O
output	O
exhibiting	O
elementary	O
tonotopic	O
features	O
that	O
indicate	O
presence	O
of	O
any	O
significant	O
tones	O
in	O
the	O
input	O
signal	O
and	O
change	O
in	O
said	O
significant	O
tones	O
over	O
time	O
.	O

The	O
system	O
comprises	O
first	O
means	O
for	O
filtering	O
the	O
input	O
signal	O
to	O
provide	O
a	O
filtered	O
output	O
,	O
said	O
output	O
indicating	O
the	O
tonotopic	O
characteristics	O
of	O
said	O
input	O
signal	O
over	O
a	O
time	O
period	O
,	O
and	O
second	O
means	O
for	O
filtering	O
the	O
output	O
to	O
determine	O
elementary	O
tonotopic	O
features	O
indicating	O
presence	O
of	O
any	O
significant	O
tones	O
indicated	O
by	O
the	O
input	O
signal	O
and	O
change	O
in	O
significant	O
tones	O
over	O
time	O
.	O
The	O
first	O
filtering	O
means	O
therefore	O
is	O
the	O
first	O
stage	O
which	O
deals	O
with	O
auditory	O
signal	O
processing	O
.	O
The	O
